.TH "SHLOCK" "1" "March 2026" "shlock 1.0.1" ""
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
shlock - file-based locking utility with stale lock detection
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]shlock\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] [\f[I]LOCKNAME\f[R]]
\f[B]\[en]\f[R] \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]\&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]shlock\f[R] provides exclusive file-based locking using
\f[B]flock\f[R](1) for safe concurrent script execution.
It prevents multiple instances of the same operation from running
simultaneously and includes automatic stale lock detection for cleanup
of locks left behind by crashed processes.
.PP
The lock is held using kernel-level \f[B]flock\f[R](1) on a lock file,
ensuring atomic lock acquisition and automatic release when the process
terminates.
A separate PID file tracks which process holds the lock for
informational purposes and stale lock validation.
The lock directory is automatically determined with fallback (see
\f[B]FILES\f[R]).
.SS Key Features
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Exclusive locking\f[R]: Only one instance of a locked operation can
run at a time
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Stale lock detection\f[R]: Automatically removes locks from dead
processes
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Flexible waiting modes\f[R]: Non-blocking, timeout-based, or
indefinite waiting
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]PID tracking\f[R]: Identifies which process holds each lock
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Lock stealing\f[R]: Administrative override to break held locks
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Clean exit handling\f[R]: Automatic cleanup on normal exit or
signal termination
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Safe for automation\f[R]: Designed for cron jobs, systemd services,
and CI/CD pipelines
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
\f[I]LOCKNAME\f[R]
Unique identifier for the lock (e.g., \[lq]backup\[rq],
\[lq]deployment\[rq], \[lq]sync\[rq]).
If omitted, automatically derived from the basename of
\f[I]COMMAND\f[R].
For example, \f[V]shlock -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh\f[R] uses lockname
\[lq]backup.sh\[rq].
.TP
\f[I]COMMAND\f[R]
Command to execute while holding the lock.
.TP
\f[I]ARGS\f[R]
Optional arguments passed to \f[I]COMMAND\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]Important\f[R]: The \f[V]--\f[R] separator is required to clearly
delineate lock options from the wrapped command and its arguments.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]-m\f[R], \f[B]\[en]max-age\f[R] \f[I]HOURS\f[R]
Maximum lock age in hours before considered stale (default: 24).
If a lock file is older than this threshold and the owning process is no
longer running, the lock is automatically removed.
.TP
\f[B]-w\f[R], \f[B]\[en]wait\f[R]
Wait indefinitely for lock to become available instead of failing
immediately.
The process will block until the lock can be acquired.
.TP
\f[B]-t\f[R], \f[B]\[en]timeout\f[R] \f[I]SECONDS\f[R]
Maximum time to wait for lock acquisition in seconds.
If the lock cannot be acquired within this time, exits with code 1.
Works independently; does not require \f[B]\[en]wait\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]-s\f[R], \f[B]\[en]steal\f[R]
Forcefully remove an existing lock.
If the lock holder process is dead, the lock is removed automatically
without prompting.
If the holder is still running, displays a warning and prompts for
confirmation before stealing.
Exits with code 1 if the user declines.
.TP
\f[B]-h\f[R], \f[B]\[en]help\f[R]
Display help message and exit.
.TP
\f[B]-V\f[R], \f[B]\[en]version\f[R]
Display version information and exit.
.PP
\f[B]Note\f[R]: Short option bundling is supported.
The argument-taking option must be last in the bundle.
For example: \f[B]-wt 60\f[R] or \f[B]-wm 12\f[R].
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Command executed successfully.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Lock acquisition failed (lock held, timeout expired, no writable lock
directory, or steal cancelled).
.TP
\f[B]2\f[R]
Invalid arguments (wrong options, missing required arguments).
.TP
\f[B]3\f[R]
Command failed (command\[cq]s exit code was non-zero).
.PP
The distinction between exit codes 1 and 3 is important for automation:
code 1 means \[lq]couldn\[cq]t run because locked\[rq], code 3 means
\[lq]ran but failed\[rq].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic Usage
.PP
Non-blocking lock (default):
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock backup -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Auto-generate lock name from command:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh
# Uses lockname \[dq]backup.sh\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Waiting Modes
.PP
Wait indefinitely for lock:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock --wait deployment -- ./deploy.sh production
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Wait up to 30 seconds:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock --timeout 30 sync -- rsync -av /src /dest
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Using short options with timeout:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock -t 60 -m 6 backup -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Cron Integration
.PP
Prevent overlapping cron jobs:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# In /etc/cron.d/backup
0 2 * * * root shlock daily-backup -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh

# If previous backup still running, this one exits immediately (code 1)
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Handle cron job failures gracefully:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# Only alert if job ran but failed (exit 3), not if locked (exit 1)
0 2 * * * root shlock backup -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh || \[rs]
  [ $? -eq 1 ] || mail -s \[dq]Backup failed\[dq] admin\[at]example.com
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Systemd Service Integration
.PP
Prevent concurrent service executions:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# /etc/systemd/system/data-sync.service
[Unit]
Description=Data Synchronization

[Service]
Type=oneshot
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/shlock data-sync -- /usr/local/bin/sync.sh
Restart=no

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
With timeout for service watchdog:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
[Service]
Type=oneshot
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/shlock --timeout 300 data-sync -- /usr/local/bin/sync.sh
TimeoutStartSec=310
\f[R]
.fi
.SS CI/CD Pipeline Integration
.PP
Serialize deployments to prevent conflicts:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# GitLab CI example
deploy:
  script:
    - shlock --timeout 600 deploy-prod -- ./deploy.sh production
  only:
    - main
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Ensure only one build per branch:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
#!/bin/bash
# build.sh
BRANCH=$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD)
shlock \[dq]build-$BRANCH\[dq] -- npm run build
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Stale Lock Handling
.PP
Custom stale lock threshold (12 hours):
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock --max-age 12 critical -- /path/to/critical.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Very short-lived locks (1 hour threshold):
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock -m 1 quick-task -- /path/to/task.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Lock Stealing
.PP
Steal a lock from a dead or running process:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock --steal backup -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Combine steal with short option bundling:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
shlock -st 30 backup -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
If the lock holder is dead, the lock is removed automatically.
If the holder is still running, \f[B]shlock\f[R] displays a warning and
prompts for confirmation.
.SS Error Handling in Scripts
.PP
Distinguish between locked and failed:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
#!/bin/bash
set -euo pipefail

if ! shlock myapp -- /path/to/command; then
  case $? in
    1) echo \[dq]Already running, skipping...\[dq] >&2; exit 0 ;;
    2) echo \[dq]Invalid arguments\[dq] >&2; exit 2 ;;
    3) echo \[dq]Command failed\[dq] >&2; exit 3 ;;
  esac
fi
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Retry logic with timeout:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
for i in {1..3}; do
  if shlock --timeout 10 myapp -- /path/to/command; then
    exit 0
  fi
  echo \[dq]Attempt $i failed, retrying...\[dq] >&2
  sleep 5
done
echo \[dq]All attempts failed\[dq] >&2
exit 1
\f[R]
.fi
.SH INTERNALS
.SS Locking Mechanism
.PP
\f[B]shlock\f[R] uses a multi-phase approach to lock acquisition:
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]Argument parsing\f[R]: Resolves \f[I]LOCKNAME\f[R] from arguments
or derives from \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] basename
.IP "2." 3
\f[B]Lock directory determination\f[R]: Selects first writable directory
from \f[V]/run/lock\f[R], \f[V]/var/lock\f[R], \f[V]/tmp/locks\f[R]
.IP "3." 3
\f[B]Stale lock check\f[R]: Validates lock age and process liveness,
removes stale locks
.IP "4." 3
\f[B]Lock stealing\f[R] (if \f[B]\[en]steal\f[R]): Removes existing
lock, prompting only if holder is still running
.IP "5." 3
\f[B]Lock acquisition\f[R]: Opens file descriptor 200 on
\f[B]/.lock\f[R] and attempts \f[B]flock\f[R](1)
.IP "6." 3
\f[B]PID tracking\f[R]: Writes current process ID to \f[B]/.pid\f[R]
.IP "7." 3
\f[B]Command execution\f[R]: Runs \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] while holding lock,
captures exit code
.IP "8." 3
\f[B]Cleanup\f[R]: EXIT trap removes PID file, \f[B]flock\f[R] releases
when fd closes
.SS File Descriptor 200
.PP
\f[B]shlock\f[R] uses file descriptor 200 for lock file operations.
This hardcoded descriptor is chosen to:
.IP \[bu] 2
Avoid conflicts with standard descriptors (0, 1, 2)
.IP \[bu] 2
Remain outside typical script descriptor ranges
.IP \[bu] 2
Provide consistent, predictable behavior
.PP
If your scripts use fd 200, this may cause conflicts.
Consider modifying \f[B]shlock\f[R] or avoiding fd 200 in wrapped
commands.
.SS Lock File Persistence
.PP
Lock files at \f[B]/.lock\f[R] are NOT deleted after use.
They persist (empty) for reuse on subsequent acquisitions.
This is intentional and follows standard \f[B]flock\f[R](1) behavior:
.IP \[bu] 2
Avoids race conditions during lock file recreation
.IP \[bu] 2
Reduces filesystem operations
.IP \[bu] 2
Enables atomic lock semantics
.PP
The PID file (\f[B]/.pid\f[R]) is temporary and removed by the EXIT trap
when the process terminates.
.SS Stale Lock Detection Algorithm
.PP
When \f[B]\[en]max-age\f[R] threshold is exceeded:
.IP "1." 3
Check if lock file exists and read its modification time
.IP "2." 3
Calculate age in seconds
.IP "3." 3
If age > \f[B]\[en]max-age\f[R] (converted to seconds):
.RS 4
.IP \[bu] 2
Read PID from \f[B]/.pid\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Check if process is still running via \f[V]kill -0 <PID>\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
If process dead: remove both \f[B].lock\f[R] and \f[B].pid\f[R] files
(stale lock cleaned)
.IP \[bu] 2
If process alive: exit with error code 1 (lock held by long-running
process)
.RE
.PP
This ensures locks from crashed processes don\[cq]t block future
executions indefinitely, while still respecting legitimately
long-running processes.
.SS Waiting Modes
.PP
Three distinct locking modes are supported:
.TP
\f[B]Non-blocking (default)\f[R]
Uses \f[V]flock -n\f[R] to fail immediately if lock is held.
Exit code 1 if locked.
.TP
\f[B]Timeout mode (\[en]timeout N)\f[R]
Uses \f[V]flock -w SECONDS\f[R] to wait up to specified time.
Exit code 1 if timeout expires.
.TP
\f[B]Indefinite wait (\[en]wait)\f[R]
Uses \f[V]flock\f[R] without flags to wait indefinitely until lock is
available.
.PP
Priority order: \f[B]\[en]timeout\f[R] > \f[B]\[en]wait\f[R] >
non-blocking.
If both \f[B]\[en]timeout\f[R] and \f[B]\[en]wait\f[R] are specified,
timeout takes precedence.
.SH INTEGRATION
.SS Systemd Timer Integration
.PP
Prevent timer-triggered services from overlapping:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# /etc/systemd/system/backup.timer
[Unit]
Description=Daily backup timer

[Timer]
OnCalendar=daily
Persistent=true

[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target
\f[R]
.fi
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# /etc/systemd/system/backup.service
[Unit]
Description=Daily backup

[Service]
Type=oneshot
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/shlock backup -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Enable with:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
systemctl enable --now backup.timer
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Cron Best Practices
.PP
Always use explicit lock names for clarity:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# Good: explicit lock name
0 2 * * * shlock daily-backup -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh

# Also good: auto-generated from command
0 2 * * * shlock -- /usr/local/bin/backup.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Use timeout to prevent infinite waits in cron:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
# Wait max 5 minutes, then fail
*/15 * * * * shlock --timeout 300 sync -- /usr/local/bin/sync.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.SS CI/CD Best Practices
.PP
Use branch-specific locks to allow parallel builds:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
LOCK=\[dq]deploy-$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD)\[dq]
shlock --timeout 900 \[dq]$LOCK\[dq] -- ./deploy.sh
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Combine with deployment gates:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
deploy:
  stage: deploy
  script:
    - shlock --timeout 600 deploy-prod -- ./deploy.sh production
  when: manual
  only:
    - main
\f[R]
.fi
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]/.lock\f[R]
Lock file used for \f[B]flock\f[R](1) operations.
Persists (empty) after use for reuse.
The location of is automatically determined (see Lock Directory
Selection below).
.TP
\f[B]/.pid\f[R]
PID file containing process ID of lock holder.
Removed by EXIT trap.
Used for informational error messages and stale lock validation.
.SS Lock Directory Selection
.PP
\f[B]shlock\f[R] automatically selects the first writable directory from
this list:
.TP
\f[B]/run/lock/\f[R]
Standard Linux lock directory (tmpfs).
World-writable with sticky bit set.
Automatically managed by \f[B]systemd-tmpfiles\f[R](8).
Cleared on reboot.
\f[B]This is the preferred location.\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]/var/lock/\f[R]
Traditional lock directory.
May persist across reboots on some systems.
Used as fallback if \f[V]/run/lock\f[R] is unavailable or not writable.
.TP
\f[B]/tmp/locks/\f[R]
Last resort directory.
Automatically created if it doesn\[cq]t exist.
Usually cleared on reboot.
Only used if both above directories are unavailable.
.PP
If none of these directories are writable, \f[B]shlock\f[R] exits with
error code 1.
.SH NOTES
.IP \[bu] 2
Lock names should be unique within your system to prevent unintended
conflicts.
.IP \[bu] 2
Lock directories on tmpfs are cleared on reboot, automatically removing
all locks.
.IP \[bu] 2
Locks are automatically released when the process terminates (normal
exit, signal, or crash).
.IP \[bu] 2
For very long-running commands, consider adjusting
\f[B]\[en]max-age\f[R] to prevent premature stale lock detection.
.IP \[bu] 2
PID reuse is possible but extremely rare; stale lock detection validates
process identity.
.SH BUGS
.PP
No known bugs.
Report issues at
<https://github.com/Open-Technology-Foundation/bash-coding-standard/issues>.
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
